description.text:
This is one of my monsters pets for the 3DArtist Mag and ThingIverse competition.
Since I don't have no experience at all with 3D printing I decided to make my monster pet all in separate pieces and with very low detail.
Not sure if this will workout good in the end, but I had to give it a go in this contest.
Feel free to post your opinion, that will help me out to improve myself in the 3D printing area.
Thanks in advance,
Miguel Redondo

Buzz is constructed according this hierarchy: Buzz
-Body
--Legs
---LeftLeg
---RightLeg
--Arms
---LeftArm
---RightArm
--Eyes
---LeftEyeSup
----LeftEye
---RightEyeSup
----RightEye
--Teeth
---LeftTooth
---RightTooth The zip files contains all those separate pieces and there is no need to glue them in order to build the Monster Pet. In order to build it just attach them in the correct place (hopefully they will fit in the holes) and orientation. The Buzz Monster Pet.stl is a ready to print file of the monster, although I have some doubts if it will work perfectly, thats why I decided to make it in pieces. So please take note that my entry is based on the separate STL files (inside the zip), since I'm really not sure if the complete one will workout.

I think that this is a very nice idea and design, I like it.
If I may, I leave here a couple of sugestions:
1: On the grid, on each hole, could you carve down the edges so that number tiles are easy to remove by pressing down on one each (and the opposite edge will lift up)
2: For the number tiles: It would be good if you had red numbers and black numbers to indicate whether they are part of the initial sudoku(red), or they have been placed by the player (black). To do so in a simple way, I would suggest that the numbers are on both sides, so that you can paint on one side with black marker and on the other side with red marker. Actually by having the numbers sticking out in relief on both side, that would make it easier to remove from the grid and my first suggestion would no longer be needed. This is a remix of the Fleishman Puzzle by plastic, based on the work of Gregg Fleishman.

The ready-to-use STL file has a thickness of 1.85 mm and a tolerance of 0.15 mm. This should be OK for well-calibrated printers, although you may want to adjust the thickness to match your layer height (including possibly thicker first layer). title: Another Duet WiFi Enclosure with Fan

description.text: This is a Duet Wifi Enclosure that takes an 80mm fan internally. The fan blows cold air on the underside of the board (where it is needed for cooling the stepper drivers) and exhausts through slots in the top and bottom of the enclosure. It is recommended that the fan is mounted using nylon nuts and bolts to ensure that there is no possibility of the bolt heads shorting on the underside of the Duet. There is access to the micro sd card as well as reset buttons etc. There are slots for cable entry on the left hand side and mounting holes on the underside. There is provision for a big ribbon cable between the cable entry slots and the lid for connecting the expansion connector. I've included the open scad file so it'd be easy enough to change the cable entry to the other side and/or change the mounting hole positions. There is also a lid - attachment by using small wood screws or self tapping screws and I've included an stl file for an 80mm finger guard.

comments.text: What size nylon nuts and bolts does this use?
comments.author: j1999t

comments.text: Assuming you mean for teh fan mounts, the holes take a 4mm diameter bolt. I think I used 30mm long ones but they could be a bit shorter (depends on how thick the fan is). I think the fans I used were 15mm thick and the case is 5 or 6 mm and you need about 4mm length for the nut so 25mm long would work with a 15mm thick fan. You don't have to use nylon bolts but if you use metal ones and a bolt came loose for any reason, it could potentially short the back of the Duet board. There is about 25mm between the back of the Duet board and the bottom of the case so you could use say a 20mm thick fan and stil have room for a 5mm "tall" bolt head but in this case, I'd definitely recommend using Nylon bolts because it'd be getting vey close to the back of the board. HTH

title: TwoPlus - Fusor Module - Chinese Jhead Support

description.text:
Soporte para clones chinos jhead minimalista y sensor LJC12A3-H-Z/BX (1-5mm) sin uso de tuercas. Diseñado para usarse con TwoPlus (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1828399) aunque no deberia haber ningun problema en adaptarse a cualquier otro sistema.

Para un funcionamiento optimo se ha de taladrar el disipador Jhead chino (DESMONTADO) para que el tubo de teflon de 4mm lo atraviese de lado a lado, de modo que el tubo de teflon tope y asiente sobre el extremo del barrel.

Printer:

Prusa i3

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Se ha de usar obligatoriamente soporte. Es preferible usar capas altas.

Requerimientos

El hueco para el paso de los tornillos que bloquearan el extrusor estan pensados para repasarse con un macho de roscar M5.

Todo a excepcion de los tornillos que bloquean al fusor debe entrar con suavidad, se puede forzar pero si algo entra duro se deberia calibrar la extrusion antes de calentarse la cabeza y dañar algo.

El sensor debe entrar muy suave, si se bloquea en algun punto se ha de retocar con una lima y a mano ya que el retoque deberia ser minimo. El sensor se bloquea en su posicion con una abrazadera de plastico relativamente fuerte (3.5mm en adelante) en su extremo inferior para que la rosca del mismo se bloquee con las marcas de las capas impresas.

Advertencia

Este soporte marcara el fusor jhead que usemos ya que ha sido diseñado para los tornillos GRIPEN sobre el aluminio. Para mi nunca ha sido un problema, llevo mucho tiempo usando este sistema pero dicho queda.

title: Pokemon Go Plus Watch Case: Rev. 2

description.text:
Pokemon Go Plus watch-style case

Put pokemon go plus on your wrist more comfortably and somewhat less conspicuously with any regular 20mm or 22mm watch band!

Two variants are provided: 38mm casing, for 20mm bands, and a 42mm casing, for 22mm bands.

All the solidworks files are available - leave a comment and I will send you the files.

REV 2: I originally chose for the button to be off-centre rather than having a larger watchface – this is due to the non-circular shape of the Pokemon Go Plus PCB. This design fixes that, with a centred button location.

PRINT SETTINGS

Front: print face down to get a smooth top surface, with supports enabled to help get better surface finish on the watch lugs. Printing without support may work for PLA with sufficient cooling as there is a 20 degree slope in the overhang area.

Back: Print the back facing down (like a dome), with supports. A small layer height helps.

I recommend using 0.1mm layers to get a smooth radius on the shell, and using a brim rather than a raft.

Some printers may have trouble with the pins on the inside of the case near the button hole. If so, just tear them off - they are not essential for a successful assembly.

ASSEMBLY

Disassemble your pokemon go, and remove the original PCB, battery, button and button gasket. Throw everything else away – especially those stupid triangle screws! If you don't have the right kind of screw driver, you can always file down a torx of suitable size to be a triangle...

Install the PCB in the front half, using the original button and rubber button gasket. Install the battery into the back half, and then screw the case closed with 4mm self-tapping wood screws. It may help to affix the battery with some blu-tak to make assembly easier. If you can't find screws that fit, you could use a small amount of superglue/hot glue and hold til dry, but you will probably have to reprint the design if you ever want to change the battery. Finally, install the 20mm watch arms of your choice!

Model files last updated: 2nd Jan 2017, 3:30am GMT+11

I'm happy with the design at this point, probably won't be updated again at this point.
Thanks for looking and happy pokemon-ing!

description.text:
This scale originally had a CR2032 in it and I had some solar cells just laying around...
With me feeling that a solar cel not being used is Soooo un-green.. I had to put them to work. Here is what I came up with. I really like this scale so it became the target of an upgrade. Due to the design of this scale, I was able to mount this device by just wedging in under the twisted arms. NO, this does NOT screw or alter the weighing sensors because they are mounted on the bottom of the scale feet. I didn't cut a slot for the exiting cable to where the CR2032 was originally housed. this allows you to either exit on top where I did, or hidden at the bottom.

The designed for Solar cells are 52 x 52 mm and put out 2.0v each.
A normal CR2032 is 3v.

With two AA's at 1.5v each and a diode to make sure the power only goes into the batteries rather than out, the voltage drop of the diode should bring the voltage really close to a good charging voltage for the two AA's in series.

Scale - ------[Cel 1]+-------[Cel 2]+-------[ Diode ]----- Scale +

Scale - ------[Bat 1]+-------[Bat 2]+----------------------- Scale +

I printed with supports and had the part I'd see all the time up so it had the best finish.
Even if your bottom looks bad, it's ok because you will never see it. :) I don't normall look under my scale.... :P

title: Parametric Wheel (Wire spool to Meccano axle adaptor)

description.text:
A simple parametric wheel with 5 cutouts made in openscad. In my case it was used to form a piece to insert into the hollow within cardboard wire spools so that they can fit on meccano axles.
Needed this as I made the mistake of buying unspooled plastic and once everything became a massive tangle realised I need a spool and somthing to help unfurl the plastic filament. Using a frame made out of mecanno and an empty carboard and aluminium spool from 24 gauge copper wire. This did work but wasn't ideal! Thankfully now almost all my plastic is bought on spools and there is a purpose built holder for them all!

• obtain empty wire spool and build meccano based spool holder
  • print 2 of the inserts
  • insert one into each side of your cardboard wire spools
  • fix the end of your filament onto the spool somehow (duct tape or bolts would be good)
  • begin the horribly slow process of spooling it up (and undoing knots in my case)
  • feed end of filament into printer
  • print unattended! YAY!

title: Modular VAWT Verticle axis wind turbine

description.text:
This is a modular VAWT that can be made on smaller printers. It can be stacked as high as needed to get the torque required for your energy production. This is a work in progress so things will change however at this point in time it fully functional.

the hub should be printed with double thick walls and at least 50 percent infill
the rods should be 100% as should the fins and the bottom bearing, top bearing should be 50%+. all of the project is designed to slot into each other part so its pretty fool proof. you can add glue if necessary. fins may need support depending on your print material.

both top and bottom bearings will need to be "seasoned" run them for a while to break them in and then add a little bit of oil. power extraction can be done via the top bearing. i found the top bearing to be most problematic, had to run it with an electric motor for half a day before it was loose enough to move freely.

video showing operation!
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rHLFTU9vK0I

100 percent infill for fins, rods, and bottom bearing. 25-100 depending on how many layers for the hub.

the rods should be a snug fit for the fins and slightly snug for the hub. add glue to these rods for actual external use.

the top cap will have a choice of gears or pulley on it. this is how the generator will be attached. the bottom bearing simply bears the weight and allows the vawt to spin. if you have a better design for the bottom/top caps please let me know!

Questo modello secondo me da molta più soddisfazione quando lo vedi volare, e sarebbe bello renderlo più godibile
L'ho fatto anche volare con un flight control (MultiWii modificato da me per funzionare su questo modello) su arduino nano con accelerometro/gyro 6 assi MPU6050 (10€ in totale di hardware), ma ha funzionato per 10 secondi per poi precipitare da 20 metri (credo sia andato in stallo, ma non ho capito bene cosa è successo)
Ultimamente si trovano in commercio stampanti di grande formato a poco prezzo (come la Creality CR-10) che hanno un volume di stampa di 30x30x40 cm...Quindi un'idea per risparmiare peso sarebbe stampare l'aereo in 4 pezzi...Ovvero Ala sx, Ala dx, Canard + Vano, Centrale+EDF, oppure anche solo avere un'ala in pezzo unico sarebbe fantastico (per l'altra poi basta specchiarla)
Poi pensavo di usare un PLA con fibra di carbonio che dicono essere estremamente rigido in modo da poter fare ancora meno infill (se non rimuoverlo del tutto, dipende da quanto è rigido il materiale, non l'ho ancora provato, oppure anche ridurre lo spessore di shell ed infill)
Queste poi sono solo idee, non ho sicuramente la tua esperienza in questo campo...

comments.text:
Vedo che nei tuoi modelli l'Esc lo metti fuori. E' così? lo fa anche un mio amico del campo per mettere una 4S e spingere con la velocità. Questa è sicuramente una modifica che farò nella prossima versione. Per quanto riguarda stampare in 4 pezzi credo che possano insorgere problemi di stampabilità. Per le ali potrei provare se fisso l'alettone con un perno da cm nel lato interno ed un perno lungo che esce dall'esterno dell'ala dall'altra parte. Per il corpo centrale non ci sarebbero piani di appoggio a meno di non usare dei supporti che personalmente non amo. Per la flight control credo sia una bella idea. description.text: MAJOR EDIT! I decided to make a large format delta printer with my grandson and the display became a problem to mount with the large dimensions of the printer. I created the original SD card holding mount to be attached to the top 20mm X 20mm rail of a delta printer. With a 42" build height and sitting on a 20-30 inch high table that was not going to work. The printer also requires the rigidity of the adjacent wall to hold down excessive motion so the flat side out placement was not optimal. This is what I came up with to make it all work. It won't be much use to you unless you do the project my way but here it is if anyone in the community that might need it. The placement and angle of the display mount will require you to elevate the bottom edge of the lower 20mm X 20mm extrusion at least 1.1" off the table top. The machine leg leveling mounts shown in the drawing are available here in my models for you to use if you like. They also act as table levelers. My apologies to anyone that made this model before this edit. That was a right hand mount and the SD card slot did not have adequate access.

description.text:
Updated to fit all bibs and now has a slot in the pin now with more spring action. You'll like my pins, I guarantee it. The tolerances are on the tight side on purpose. A very light sanding of the hole in the top piece can custom fit it to the thickness of your clothing of choice.

As a new runner to races and as an owner of a 3D Printer it seemed silly to use the same safety pins I used on my kids to attach the 'runner bib' aka the number to my shirt. Taking a queue from the attachments I have on some tarps to create attachment points for lines I came up with this little two part clip.

You put the part with the post on the inside of your shirt, you press your bib onto the post, part of you shirt will come through the hole pressed out by the pin, then you put the other part on the outside of the shirt and it'll capture the bit of shirt with your bib stuck between them. So outer piece, bib, shirt, inner piece. You can go the other way but then the pins might poke you, I made them a little long on purpose so they accommodate thicker shirts.

The outer piece has a step on one side, I use this for the outside to give the cloth of the shirt a place to expand into to help lock it down.

The edges are rounded but should print fine on any printer. The glass side will be against your skin and should provide a smooth non-irritating surface.

The ones I use on tarps actually have oval holes and pins with a slot so you twist them to lock them down but I didn't want to be twisting clips on my shirts for fear of cutting a thread or something so it's just a push through. Which seems to work okay. THey held up for my first 5K without any problem.

The pin versus the hole is deliberately a little on the tight side so you can take a piece of sandpaper and just smooth down the hole to reduce any risk of messing up your shirt and tailor the opening to your shirts thickness. For me, a quick hit with some 220 grit smooths thing thing out and makes a perfect fit.

I've since found out there is a commercial product that does pretty much the same thing and arguably probably lasts longer than this one 3D printed. But at $0.36 a set of four (based on what I paid for my current on the printer spool of Hatchbox) printed in PLA versus a few dollars I'll stick with printing my own. And if I lose a piece, well I don't plan on running that many races a year so if I have to print a full set every couple of years, well it's 36 cents and about 20 minutes.

If you like my work I hope you'll consider supporting me on Pateron: https://www.patreon.com/3DPrintingProfessor Subscribe to me on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/user/mrjoesays Write secret messages to your friends. Find out how to use this ring on Youtube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8-q2hLL3Fco

Write secret messages to your friends and decode them with this ring. The Caesar Cipher, or Shift Cipher, is one of the oldest and simplest codes. Simply shift the alphabet by some amount and use that alphabet to write your message, or in this case twist the rings so that the letters line up in the right order. This is actually 2 nested rings that print interlocked but twist independently. It's big enough to fit on a finger tho it may be too big for regular wear. How to use: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8-q2hLL3Fco Both ends of the message chain will need a ring. To encode the message first choose a letter to be the key for the message. Then twist the rings so that "A" on the top ring aligns with the secret letter key. Write the key as the first letter of the message, then proceed to encode the message by looking for the letter you want to encode on the top ring, but writing the letter on the bottom ring. To decode the message, twist the rings to that "A" on the top ring aligns with the first letter of the message (the key). Then find each letter in the message on the bottom ring, writing down the letter above it on the top ring until the message is revealed. H:FVB HYL H ZWF UVD If you don't have a 3D printer, order a set for yourself on my etsy store: https://www.etsy.com/your/shops/CymonsDesigns/tools/listings/259345625
